<FindBugsFilter
    xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0 https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotbugs/spotbugs/4.8.6/spotbugs/etc/findbugsfilter.xsd">

    <!--
        HelpMojo is generated by maven-plugin-plugin from plugin.xml at build time
        (target/generated-sources/plugin/.../HelpMojo.java). The source is never on
        disk in src/, is regenerated on every `mvn package`, and is not under project
        control: fixing the lint findings would require forking the generator. The
        full set of generated-source patterns is suppressed for this class only.

        Pattern-by-pattern rationale:
          - XXE_DOCUMENT: the generator emits a DocumentBuilder.parse() of the
            in-JAR plugin-help.xml descriptor without setting the secure-processing
            features. The input is the plugin's own resource, not user input.
          - IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_TOSTRING: no toString on the generated class.
          - IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_WRONG_FIELD_ORDER: instance fields appear before
            static fields in the generated source.
          - AI_ANNOTATION_ISSUES_NEEDS_NULLABLE: two methods (findSingleChild,
            getPropertyFromExpression) return null on missing-element paths but
            the generator does not annotate the return type @Nullable.
          - WEM_WEAK_EXCEPTION_MESSAGING: the generated build() throws with a
            static "Unable to read the help file" string; no state context is
            available because the failure happens before the doc tree is bound.
          - UI_INHERITANCE_UNSAFE_GETRESOURCE: getClass().getResource(...) inside
            build() loads "plugin-help.xml" from the same JAR; HelpMojo is emitted
            as a leaf class per goal and subclassing is not a realistic threat.
          - SPP_FIELD_COULD_BE_STATIC: the generated `goal` field is instance-
            scoped because the generator emits one HelpMojo per plugin; making it
            static would require a generator change we don't own.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.llamacpp_ai_index_maven_plugin.HelpMojo"/>
        <Or>
            <Bug pattern="XXE_DOCUMENT"/>
            <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_TOSTRING"/>
            <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_WRONG_FIELD_ORDER"/>
            <Bug pattern="AI_ANNOTATION_ISSUES_NEEDS_NULLABLE"/>
            <Bug pattern="WEM_WEAK_EXCEPTION_MESSAGING"/>
            <Bug pattern="UI_INHERITANCE_UNSAFE_GETRESOURCE"/>
            <Bug pattern="SPP_FIELD_COULD_BE_STATIC"/>
        </Or>
    </Match>

    <!--
        SPP_FIELD_COULD_BE_STATIC on Maven @Parameter instance fields on the
        project's own Mojos (GenerateMojo, AggregatePackagesMojo, AggregateProjectMojo).

        fb-contrib flags @Parameter fields on each Mojo (e.g. pluginVersion,
        aiVersion, llamaContextSize, llamaThreads on the generate/aggregate-packages
        goals; pluginVersion, aiVersion, projectName on aggregate-project) as
        "assigned at most once, could be static" purely from bytecode shape. The rule is wrong for
        Maven @Parameter fields by contract:

            // Maven's per-execution wiring (simplified):
            GenerateMojo mojo = new GenerateMojo();              // no-arg ctor
            for (Field f : mojo.getClass().getDeclaredFields()) {
                if (f.isAnnotationPresent(Parameter.class)) {
                    f.setAccessible(true);
                    f.set(mojo, resolveParameterValue(f));        // INSTANCE field
                }
            }
            mojo.execute();

        A static field would be shared JVM-wide and would skip per-execution
        injection &#x2014; the &lt;configuration&gt; block in a user's POM would
        never reach it. fb-contrib has no model of Maven's plugin contract; this
        is a structural false positive that source changes cannot resolve.

        Suppression scoped narrowly to the three concrete Mojos so any genuine
        SPP finding on non-Mojo code still surfaces. AbstractAiIndexMojo's
        shared @Parameter fields don't trigger SPP because they're written
        from multiple subclasses.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.GenerateMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.AggregatePackagesMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.AggregateProjectMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.CalibrateMojo"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="SPP_FIELD_COULD_BE_STATIC"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS on Maven plugin Mojos.

        AbstractAiIndexMojo and its concrete subclasses (GenerateMojo,
        AggregatePackagesMojo) are Maven Mojo instances. Maven instantiates one
        per execution via reflection, populates @Parameter fields via setter
        injection, calls execute(), then discards the instance. Mojos are
        managed by identity (Maven keeps no map keyed on a Mojo instance), and
        no project code compares two Mojos for value equality.

        Generating a value-equality equals here would:
          - Not change runtime behaviour (no caller compares Mojos by value).
          - Create a false impression that Mojos are value objects, encouraging
            future readers to put them in Sets/Maps where the mutable @Parameter
            fields would silently break the invariants.
          - Need a callSuper=true chain through AbstractMojo (which extends
            Object directly and has no fields that participate in equality), so
            the generated method would just be (this == that) wrapped in a
            field-by-field comparison of plugin-injected @Parameter values.

        Identity equality (the default from Object) is the correct semantics
        for a Maven Mojo.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.AbstractAiIndexMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.AggregatePackagesMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.GenerateMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.CalibrateMojo"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS on Maven @Parameter configuration POJOs.

        AiFieldGenerationConfig and AiPromptDefinition are mutable JavaBean
        POJOs that the Maven plugin framework instantiates via reflection,
        populates through setters, and stores in a List<...> @Parameter field
        on the parent Mojo. No code path compares two instances for value
        equality; the surrounding Mojo iterates the list in source order and
        uses the (non-null) string keys (promptKey, aiDefinitionKey,
        AiPromptDefinition.key) to drive lookups against the other registries.

        Generating a value-equality equals over their mutable fields would:
          - Mislead readers into thinking these are immutable value types.
          - Make Set/Map semantics dependent on the Maven framework's
            population order (the values are mutable until setter injection
            completes).
          - Force a reciprocal hashCode that violates the immutability
            assumption hashCode contracts depend on.

        Identity is the correct semantics for a Maven @Parameter JavaBean.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFieldGenerationConfig"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.prompt.AiPromptDefinition"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS on the AiModelDefinitionSupport service.

        AiModelDefinitionSupport is a service/lookup class: it owns a
        Map<String, AiGenerationConfig> built once from the @Parameter
        definitions list, and exposes a get(key) lookup. It is constructed
        once per Mojo execution, held inside the Mojo, and discarded. No
        code path stores two AiModelDefinitionSupport instances in a Set/Map
        keyed by value, and the underlying map is mutable by design (Maven
        plugin framework populates the source list of definitions via
        reflection during Mojo configuration).

        Identity is the correct semantics for a stateful service object.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiModelDefinitionSupport"/>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS on the AiSourceExcludeFilter matcher.

        AiSourceExcludeFilter is a stateless matcher: it compiles its @Parameter-derived
        glob patterns into a List<Pattern> once at construction and exposes a single
        isExcluded(path) predicate. It is built once per generate execution, held inside
        SourceFileIndexer, and discarded. No code path stores two filter instances in a
        Set/Map keyed by value or compares two filters for value equality; the compiled
        Pattern list is an implementation detail, not an identity.

        Generating a value-equality equals over the compiled patterns would mislead
        readers into treating the matcher as a value object and would compare
        java.util.regex.Pattern instances, which themselves use identity equality (two
        Patterns compiled from the same source are not equal). Identity is the correct
        semantics for this helper, matching AiModelDefinitionSupport above.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.support.AiSourceExcludeFilter"/>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        USBR_UNNECESSARY_STORE_BEFORE_RETURN on Lombok-generated equals / hashCode /
        canEqual / toString.

        Lombok's @EqualsAndHashCode and @ToString annotation processors inject the
        textbook polynomial-hash bytecode pattern (and lombok.config already emits
        @lombok.Generated on every synthetic member via
        lombok.addLombokGeneratedAnnotation = true):

            int result = 1;
            result = result * 59 + ($field == null ? 43 : $field.hashCode());
            ...
            return result;          // USBR fires here, on the istore_N / iload_N / ireturn triplet

        SpotBugs core honours @lombok.Generated and skips its own detectors on those
        members, but the fb-contrib plugin's USBR detector does NOT &#x2014; fb-contrib
        is a separate plugin family with its own filter pipeline. Suppressing USBR on
        equals / hashCode / canEqual / toString matches every method name Lombok can
        emit. The collateral cost is small: any handwritten member of those four names
        that genuinely stores-then-immediately-returns is either a debugger-friendly
        local-variable pattern or a micro-optimisation, both intentional here.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Method name="equals"/>
            <Method name="hashCode"/>
            <Method name="canEqual"/>
            <Method name="toString"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="USBR_UNNECESSARY_STORE_BEFORE_RETURN"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        FORMAT_STRING_MANIPULATION on the prompt-template pipeline.

        The plugin's whole contract is "developers write prompt templates in their POM
        &lt;configuration&gt; and the plugin substitutes per-file context into them via
        String.format". The template comes from operator-controlled POM XML (parsed and
        validated by Maven at build time), not from end-user request input. A malformed
        template raises IllegalFormatException on first use, immediately surfacing the
        configuration error.

        Three sites all trace to the same data path:
          - Java8CompatibilityHelper#formatted -&gt; String.format(template, args)
          - AiPromptSupport#buildPrompt -&gt; templates.get(promptKey) -&gt; formatted(...)

        Restructuring to escape user-supplied format specifiers would defeat the
        configurable-templates feature; suppression is the right answer here.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.support.Java8CompatibilityHelper"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.prompt.AiPromptSupport"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="FORMAT_STRING_MANIPULATION"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        AI_ANNOTATION_ISSUES_NEEDS_NULLABLE on GenerateMojo.resolveFileExtensions.

        The method body returns either compatibilityHelper.listOf(DEFAULT_FILE_EXTENSION)
        (non-null by contract) or the @Parameter-injected fileExtensions list, gated by
        an early-return guard that ensures the second branch only runs when the field
        is non-null and non-empty. The method provably cannot return null.

        fb-contrib&apos;s analyzer is conservative: it sees a field-load on a Maven
        @Parameter field (no model for the @NullMarked + ExcludedFieldAnnotations
        wiring) and assumes the second return path may propagate null. We tried
        hoisting the field to a local variable to give fb-contrib a clearer dataflow
        signal; the finding persisted. Adding @Nullable to the return would be a lie
        about the contract (the method genuinely cannot return null).

        Suppression is scoped narrowly to this one method.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.GenerateMojo"/>
        <Method name="resolveFileExtensions"/>
        <Bug pattern="AI_ANNOTATION_ISSUES_NEEDS_NULLABLE"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        DCN_NULLPOINTER_EXCEPTION on AbstractAiIndexMojo.buildPromptSupport /
        buildAiModelDefinitionSupport.

        fb-contrib's general rule is "do not catch NullPointerException" — sound
        advice when NPE indicates a bug. Our two catch sites are the deliberate
        translation bridge between the support classes' Objects.requireNonNull
        validation (which throws NPE by Java convention with the rich
        index + bad-entry message) and Maven's MojoExecutionException (which the
        framework treats as a user configuration error rather than a plugin bug).

        The alternatives we considered and rejected:
          - Throw IllegalArgumentException from the support ctors via a manual
            (x == null) check: brings back the RCN_REDUNDANT_NULLCHECK_OF_NONNULL_VALUE
            findings that started this chain.
          - Pre-validate inside the Mojo before calling the ctor: duplicates the
            validation logic and lets the ctor accept malformed input, which is
            a footgun for any non-Mojo caller (tests, future programmatic API).
          - Pull in Guava Preconditions.checkNotNull: adds a dep purely to dodge
            one detector rule.

        Scoping to these two methods (not class-wide) means any other NPE-catching
        site on AbstractAiIndexMojo would still surface.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.AbstractAiIndexMojo"/>
        <Or>
            <Method name="buildPromptSupport"/>
            <Method name="buildAiModelDefinitionSupport"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="DCN_NULLPOINTER_EXCEPTION"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        OPM_OVERLY_PERMISSIVE_METHOD on AiProgressBar.render. fb-contrib flags the public render(...)
        overloads as "could be more restrictive" from bytecode shape, but they are the class's public API
        (a reusable progress-bar renderer) and are called from GenerateMojo and exercised directly by unit
        tests. Same rationale as the AiGenerationTimeEstimator OPM suppression above.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.support.AiProgressBar"/>
        <Bug pattern="OPM_OVERLY_PERMISSIVE_METHOD"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        THROWS_METHOD_THROWS_RUNTIMEEXCEPTION on AiFieldGenerationSupport.generateWithOverflowRetry.
        fb-contrib flags the `throw e` as a method throwing a RuntimeException, but this is not raising a
        new unchecked exception as control flow - it RE-THROWS the provider's own caught exception to
        propagate it unchanged (the retry loop only intercepts a context-overflow, identified by message,
        and otherwise gives up by rethrowing). The provider (JNI binding) throws an unchecked
        LlamaException; catching a more specific type would couple the indexer to the binding, which the
        message-based detection deliberately avoids. Scoped to the one retry method.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.indexer.AiFieldGenerationSupport"/>
        <Method name="generateWithOverflowRetry"/>
        <Bug pattern="THROWS_METHOD_THROWS_RUNTIMEEXCEPTION"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        OPM_OVERLY_PERMISSIVE_METHOD on AiFactDefinitionSupport.facts. fb-contrib flags the public facts(key)
        as "could be more restrictive" from bytecode shape (it is called from resolveFactsKeys in the same
        class), but it is the class's public lookup API and is exercised directly by unit tests. Same
        rationale as the AiGenerationTimeEstimator / AiProgressBar OPM suppressions.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFactDefinitionSupport"/>
        <Bug pattern="OPM_OVERLY_PERMISSIVE_METHOD"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        DCN_NULLPOINTER_EXCEPTION on GenerateMojo.resolveSharedFacts. Same deliberate translation bridge as
        AbstractAiIndexMojo.buildPromptSupport (see that suppression's rationale): AiFactDefinitionSupport's
        Objects.requireNonNull validation throws NPE by Java convention on a null definition key, which this
        method catches and rethrows as a Maven MojoExecutionException (a user configuration error) rather
        than a plugin bug. Scoped to the one method.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.GenerateMojo"/>
        <Method name="resolveSharedFacts"/>
        <Bug pattern="DCN_NULLPOINTER_EXCEPTION"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        EI_EXPOSE_REP / EI_EXPOSE_REP2 on the <calibration> accessors of the Maven @Parameter config beans
        (AiModelDefinition, AiGenerationConfig). Same rationale as the routing-config EI suppression above:
        these are mutable JavaBeans the plugin framework populates via reflection; the AiCalibration the
        getter returns / the setter stores IS the configuration, read once during the run and never shared
        across threads. A defensive copy would deep-clone an immutable-after-injection value for no gain.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiModelDefinition"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiGenerationConfig"/>
        </Or>
        <Or>
            <Method name="getCalibration"/>
            <Method name="setCalibration"/>
        </Or>
        <Or>
            <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP"/>
            <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
        </Or>
    </Match>


    <!--
        EI_EXPOSE_REP / EI_EXPOSE_REP2 on the rule-routing config beans and the routing-plan model.

        AiCondition / AiConditionGroup / AiFieldGenerationConfig are mutable Maven @Parameter
        JavaBeans: the plugin framework instantiates them via reflection and populates the nested
        condition tree (and/or/not groups, the AiRangeCondition size/lines, the extensions list)
        through setters during Mojo configuration. The "exposed representation" IS the configuration
        by contract - the indexer reads the very tree Maven built and never mutates or shares it
        across threads (the build is single-threaded and the beans are discarded after the run).
        Defensive copies in the getters/setters would deep-clone an immutable-after-injection config
        tree for no safety gain and would break the "read the configured tree" model.

        AiIndexPlan (+ its nested Entry) is a build-time DTO produced by SourceFileIndexer.classify
        and consumed only by AiIndexPlan.renderMarkdown and the unit tests. Its routesByModel / skipped
        / unmatched collections and Entry.rule reference the same single-threaded, throwaway data; the
        Entry.rule is the shared routing rule (an AiFieldGenerationConfig) and is intentionally aliased,
        not copied. No untrusted caller can mutate shared state through these accessors.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiCondition"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiConditionGroup"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFieldGenerationConfig"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFactDefinition"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.indexer.AiIndexPlan"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.indexer.AiIndexPlan$Entry"/>
        </Or>
        <Or>
            <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP"/>
            <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
        </Or>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS on routing value/config helpers, matching the existing
        suppressions for the other Maven @Parameter POJOs and stateless helpers above.

        AiConditionGroup and AiRangeCondition are mutable Maven @Parameter beans (populated via
        setters, never compared by value). AiFileContext is a build-time per-file context record
        built by the indexer and read once during classification; nothing stores two of them in a
        Set/Map keyed by value. Identity is the correct semantics; a value-equality equals would
        falsely imply these are interned value objects.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiConditionGroup"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiRangeCondition"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFileContext"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFactCounter"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFactDefinition"/>
        </Or>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_EQUALS"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_TOSTRING on AiIndexPlan: it is an internal DTO whose human-readable
        form is the purpose-built renderMarkdown(...) (a structured Markdown plan), not a debug
        toString. A generated toString over its nested maps would duplicate that intent and never
        be called. Matches the HelpMojo IMC suppression rationale above.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.indexer.AiIndexPlan"/>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_NO_TOSTRING"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_WRONG_FIELD_ORDER on LlamaCppJniAiGenerationProvider: fb-contrib wants
        the static REUSE_SLOT_ID constant declared before the instance fields. The current order
        (the constant sits with the slot-reuse logic it documents) is a deliberate readability
        choice and has no runtime effect.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.provider.LlamaCppJniAiGenerationProvider"/>
        <Bug pattern="IMC_IMMATURE_CLASS_WRONG_FIELD_ORDER"/>
    </Match>

    <!--
        fb-contrib stylistic/opinion detectors on the routing + plan + estimator code. These are
        bytecode-shape heuristics that source changes cannot resolve without harming readability or
        the class's intended API, scoped narrowly to the affected classes:

          - CE_CLASS_ENVY: buildLlamaCppJniConfig copies the resolved AiGenerationConfig field-by-field
            into the immutable LlamaCppJniConfig (it necessarily touches that config's getters more than
            its own state); AiConditionEvaluator.branchCount walks the AiCondition tree. Both are
            translation/traversal methods - referencing the other type heavily is the point.
          - OCP_OVERLY_CONCRETE_PARAMETER: parameters typed to the concrete collaborator the method
            actually needs (AiCondition / Map) rather than an over-abstracted supertype.
          - OPM_OVERLY_PERMISSIVE_METHOD: the estimator's estimate* helpers and the plan's
            routedCount/totalEstimatedSeconds are public by design - they are the class API and are
            exercised directly by unit tests.
          - UCPM_USE_CHARACTER_PARAMETERIZED_METHOD: renderMarkdown appends short literal strings
            for the Markdown template; spelling them as String literals keeps the template readable.
          - WEM_WEAK_EXCEPTION_MESSAGING: the AiConditionEvaluator.validate and GenerateMojo.execute
            messages describe a POM configuration error in operator terms; they intentionally read as
            user-facing config diagnostics rather than carrying internal state.
          - RCN_REDUNDANT_NULLCHECK_OF_NONNULL_VALUE: arises from the Objects.requireNonNull /
            @NullMarked validation style (see the DCN rationale above); the explicit guards are the
            deliberate fail-fast contract, not dead checks.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Or>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiConditionEvaluator"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFieldGenerationSelector"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiFactExtractor"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.indexer.AiIndexPlan"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.support.AiGenerationTimeEstimator"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.AbstractAiIndexMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.GenerateMojo"/>
            <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.mojo.CalibrateMojo"/>
        </Or>
        <Or>
            <Bug pattern="CE_CLASS_ENVY"/>
            <Bug pattern="OCP_OVERLY_CONCRETE_PARAMETER"/>
            <Bug pattern="OCP_OVERLY_CONCRETE_COLLECTION_PARAMETER"/>
            <Bug pattern="OPM_OVERLY_PERMISSIVE_METHOD"/>
            <Bug pattern="UCPM_USE_CHARACTER_PARAMETERIZED_METHOD"/>
            <Bug pattern="WEM_WEAK_EXCEPTION_MESSAGING"/>
            <Bug pattern="RCN_REDUNDANT_NULLCHECK_OF_NONNULL_VALUE"/>
        </Or>
    </Match>

    <!--
        IMPROPER_UNICODE on AiOversizeStrategy.fromConfig. The findsecbugs detector flags any
        case-insensitive comparison (equalsIgnoreCase, and likewise toLowerCase/toUpperCase) because
        Unicode case folding can change string length for some scripts. Here the compared values are a
        fixed, closed set of ASCII config tokens (fail/sample/mapReduce/deterministic) authored by the
        operator in POM XML, not user/locale text; matching a configured &lt;onOversize&gt; value
        case-insensitively is the intended, safe behaviour. Scoped to the one parsing method.
    -->
    <Match>
        <Class name="net.ladenthin.maven.llamacpp.aiindex.config.AiOversizeStrategy"/>
        <Method name="fromConfig"/>
        <Bug pattern="IMPROPER_UNICODE"/>
    </Match>

</FindBugsFilter>
